  <h2>What is diceware?</h2>
  <p>
    Diceware builds a passphrase by picking random words from a fixed list. With
    the EFF large list of 7,776 words, each word contributes log₂(7776) ≈ 12.925
    bits of entropy, so a six-word passphrase has about 77.5 bits — enough to
    resist offline cracking even against well-funded attackers, and far easier
    to remember than random characters.
  </p>

  <h2>Where does the list come from?</h2>
  <p>
    The wordlist is the EFF large wordlist for passphrases (published 2016-07-18),
    licensed under CC-BY-3.0. A copy lives in this site's repository at
    <code>{{ wordlists.eff_large_v1.url }}</code> so you can audit exactly what
    you ran. The SHA-256 of that file is pinned in the page source
    (<code>{{ wordlists.eff_large_v1.sha256 }}</code>) and verified by your
    browser before any word is drawn — if the file has been tampered with, the
    generator refuses to run. Upstream source:
    <a href="https://www.eff.org/files/2016/07/18/eff_large_wordlist.txt" rel="noopener">eff.org/files/2016/07/18/eff_large_wordlist.txt</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>How random is this, really?</h2>
  <p>
    Words are drawn with <code>crypto.getRandomValues</code> — the browser's
    cryptographically secure RNG — using rejection sampling to guarantee a
    uniform distribution over the 7,776 words. No <code>Math.random</code>,
    no predictable seeds. The page ships no telemetry and makes no network
    requests after the wordlist loads (subsequent visits serve it from your
    browser's Cache Storage).
  </p>

  <h2>What the crack-time figures mean</h2>
  <p>
    The numbers above are rough average-case estimates: time to brute-force an
    unknown passphrase, assuming the attacker knows it's a diceware phrase of
    the shown length. Three attacker profiles are shown — an online service that
    throttles to ~10 guesses/sec, an offline attacker against a fast hash like
    NTLM (~10<sup>11</sup> guesses/sec on a modern GPU), and an offline attacker
    against a slow KDF like argon2 or bcrypt with sensible parameters
    (~10<sup>4</sup> guesses/sec). Real-world attacker rates vary, so treat
    these as order-of-magnitude figures.
  </p>
